The rest of this file is
Historical notes and prompt chunks below.  Not useful anymore.
------------------------------------------------------------------------

In general when an autolisp error occurs, we will want to be able to
find the exact form that signaled the error (form, source file, line,
column).

This means that the load (and vlisp-compile) reader should track the
source file, and position (line, column), and record it with symbols,
or provide a way to retrieve it.

This means that error signaling operators must be instrumented to
provide the caller (source of the error signaling).

This info may be attached to the CL conditions, and retrieved for
reporting and debugging.



Note that this will be a debugger for autolisp programs, interpreted
or compiled by a Common Lisp implementation. The debugger is
implemented in Common Lisp, and bordeaux-threads are available, as
well as the condition system, in the implementation language. But
there's no notion of a condition system in autolisp, just a *ERROR*
handler in a variable, and VL-CATCH-ALL-APPLY, VL-CATCH-ALL-ERROR-P,
VL-CATCH-ALL-ERROR-MESSAGE. But happily, we're implementing the
debugger in Common Lisp!

Now, while specifying the clautolisp debugger, we want to have ahet
modular and pluggable user interface for the debugger.

Basically 3 UI:

- dumb terminal user interface.
- 2D terminal user interface (ncurses via cl-charms or PDCurses).
- emacs user interface (kind of like sldb from slime).

The autolisp reader alread tracks the source and position of symbols,
and other tokens, so the debugger and debugger user interface can
refer to the source files to display them and "interact" with them
(eg. move the cursor into a form to drop a break point), or move the
cursor to the current form in step mode, etc.

We also need to specify an inspector (it's basically independent from
the debugger, but the debugger may use the inspector to display the
variables and let the user navigate thru its contents (lists,
entities, etc).
This inspector will be also accessible and usable thru the 3 UI.

   +------------+
   |  autolisp  |
   |  program   |                  debugger
   +------------+                   UI API
         |                            ^
   +------------+     +----------+    |    +-------------+
   | clautolisp |-----| debugger |----|----| debugger UI |
   +------------+     +----------+    |    +-------------+
         |                 |          v
+-----------------+        |
|   Common Lisp   |--------+
| implementation  |
+-----------------+


debugger UI is one of dumb terminal debugger ui,
ncurses terminal debugger ui, or emacs debugger ui.

So, you may wrap up a complete specification for the clautolisp
debugger, with its user interfaces, and the internal interfaces with
the required autolisp implementation data structures.


Currently, clautolisp is implemented as an interpreter.  However, we
will probably have to implement a compiler, targetting Common Lisp and
generating to CL functions from one autolisp function (one "native"
and one for debugging, ie, instrumentalised). So the debugger
specification may specify the required elements from such autolisp
compiled to common lisp code (the instrumentalisation required).

Be sure to quote Robert Strand works, papers and sources, and (bibtex
like stuff).

